  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Hydrogen is the lightest element and the first element in the periodic table. It has three isotopes: protium (no neutron), deuterium (one neutron), and tritium (two neutrons). In the laboratory, hydrogen is prepared by reacting zinc with dilute sulfuric acid: Zn + H₂SO₄ → ZnSO₄ + H₂. It is collected by downward displacement of water. Industrially, hydrogen is produced by the Bosch process or electrolysis of water. Hydrogen is colorless, odorless, tasteless, and the lightest gas. It is highly combustible and burns with a pale blue flame producing water. The 'pop' sound test is used to identify hydrogen. Uses include fuel cells, ammonia manufacture, and hydrogenation of oils.",
    "rules": [
      "Hydrogen: lightest element, atomic number 1",
      "Isotopes: protium (¹H), deuterium (²H), tritium (³H)",
      "Lab preparation: Zn + dil. H₂SO₄ → ZnSO₄ + H₂",
      "Collection: downward displacement of water (insoluble in water)",
      "Physical properties: colorless, odorless, lightest gas",
      "Burns with pale blue flame: 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O",
      "Test: burning splint gives 'pop' sound",
      "Reducing agent: removes oxygen from metal oxides",
      "Uses: fuel cells, ammonia synthesis, hydrogenation"
    ]
